Generally if you meet people who have spent their youth partying every night, vacationing, socializing in big friend groups, etc. they will feel regret and have the sensation of lost time even more strongly than those who "missed out". The only way to win is to have a big family.

It feels a bit crass saying it bluntly like this but people should focus on life goals rather than life experiences. If you have a house and a family with like 10 children when you're 50 you won't really care about whatever party you cancelled your plans for. It's meaningless.

Not that most people today couldn't do with a bit more partying, "experiences", and "doing things" and it doesn't reflect societal problems, but there are few things sadder than a 50 year old partygoer who wasted his life. People should get smart and start hitting the real goals.

I think this is a key distinction between people working in medicine (doctors, nurses, etc.) and normies, a 90 year old person able to hold a job is so so much better than someone rotting in a nursing with home with Alzheimer's. It's so much better to work than rot in retirement.

I guess the ideal retirement of focusing on a lifelong hobby like woodworking, gardening, going on hikes with your grandchildren and helping around the house or hanging out with grandpa bros is even better but doing a part time job is still 10x more dignified than a nursing home.
Yeah a full time job would be a bit too much probably but part time is perfect imo

I still think 40 hours to survive is better than a nursing home, even really brutal conditions will be psychologically better than feeling superfluous and helpless, like how in prisons aggressive environment is less crushing than total isolation... but obviously far from ideal
